nd, United Kingdom":"Pilton, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Nettlecombe, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Nettlecombe, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Bourbouncy, Loe-Et-Garonne, Aquitaine, France":"Aquitaine, Frankrig"},"nl":{"1040–1100":"1040–1100","1040–1066":"1040–1066","1065–1101":"1065–1101","1001–1052":"1001–1052","1005–1059":"1005–1059","1005":"1005","1059":"1059","1101":"1101","1100":"1100","1001":"1001","1066":"1066","1065":"1065","14 October 1066, killed in the Battle of Hastings":"14 oktober 1066","1052":"1052","1040":"1040","Hastings, Sussex, England":"Hastings, Sussex, England","Pilton, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Pilton, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Nettlecombe, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Nettlecombe, Somerset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bourbouncy, Loe-Et-Garonne, Aquitaine, France":"Aquitaine, Frankrijk"},"en":{"1040–1100":"1040–1100","1040–1066":"1040–1066","1065–1101":"1065–1101","1001–1052":"1001–1052","1005–1059":"1005–1059","1005":"1005","1059":"1059","1101":"1101","1100":"1100","1001":"1001","1066":"1066","1065":"1065","14 October 1066, killed in the Battle of Hastings":"14 October 1066","1052":"1052","1040":"1040","Hastings, Sussex, England":"Hastings, Sussex, England","Pilton, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Pilton, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Nettlecombe, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Nettlecombe, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Bourbouncy, Loe-Et-Garonne, Aquitaine, France":"Aquitaine, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Gand","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Hyman, Isidor, Myer.","English, German, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): metonymic occupational name for a maker of hoops and bands, etc., from Middle English <i>band</i>, <i>bond</i>, Middle High German, Middle Low German <i>bant</i>, German <i>Band</i> ‘hoop, metal band, fetter, shackle’, i.e. something used for tying or binding.","English: variant of   Bond  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bandt","meanings":["German: variant of   Band  ."]},{"name":"Bandstra","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Dutch Gerrit, Wouter.","West Frisian: habitational name composed with   Band   4 + the suffix <i>-stra</i> from Old Frisian <i>sittera</i> ‘inhabitant of’."]},{"name":"Banta","meanings":["West Frisian: probably a habitational name for someone from Bant, in the 17th century an island in Friesland, now a village north of Emmeloord in the Noordoostpolder (see   Band   4, compare   Banda   5). This surname is no longer found in the Netherlands.","History: Epke Jacobs Banta arrived in New Netherland in 1659."]},{"name":"Bandel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Zvi, Emanuel, Hyman, Meir.","South German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): from a diminutive of   Band  . See also   Bendel  .","German: in some cases, a variant of <b>Pandel</b>, a pet form of the medieval personal name <i>Pantaleon</i> (see   Pantaleo  )."]},{"name":"Bend","meanings":["English (Leicestershire and Nottinghamshire): from Middle English <i>bend</i> ‘band, fetter, chain; ribbon, sash, stripe’, for someone who made, wore, or used such items. See also the   Band   1 and compare   Bendy   1."]},{"name":"Bandler","meanings":["German: occupational name for a maker of band (for vessels) or ribbon or lace, from an agent derivative of Middle High German <i>bandel</i>, a diminutive of <i>bant</i> ‘band’ (see   Band  )."]},{"name":"Bandy","meanings":["English: perhaps from an unrecorded Middle English <i>bandi</i>, <i>bondi</i>, <i>bendi</i>, derivatives of Middle English and Old English <i>band</i>, <i>bond</i>, <i>bend</i> ‘band, ribbon, stripe’ + Middle English <i>-i</i>, reinforced by Old French <i>bendé</i> ‘striped’, with reference perhaps to clothing ornamented with ribbons or stripes, or to the diagonal band of a heraldic device. Compare   Band  .","English: alternatively, perhaps from an unrecorded Middle English <i>bandy</i>, <i>bendy</i> ‘curved stick’, used for someone with bent or crooked legs.","Czech and Slovak: from a derivative of <i>banda</i> ‘(gipsy) band’, apparently a nickname for a bandsman. This surname is found among Gypsies."]},{"name":"Bond","meanings":["English: status name for a peasant farmer or husbandman, Middle English <i>bond(e)</i>, <i>bounde</i>, occasionally <i>bande</i> ‘bondman, customary tenant, serf’ (Old English <i>bonda</i>, <i>bunda</i>, reinforced by Old Norse <i>bóndi</i>). The Old Norse word was also in use as a personal name (Old Norse <i>Bóndi</i>, <i>Bondi</i>, <i>Bundi</i>, <i>Bonde</i>, borrowed as late Old English <i>Bonda</i>), and this has given rise to other English and Scandinavian surnames alongside those originating as status names, such as the Middle English personal name <i>Bonde</i>. The status of the peasant farmer fluctuated considerably during the Middle Ages; moreover, the underlying ancient Germanic word is of disputed origin and meaning. Among ancient Germanic peoples who settled to an agricultural life, the term came to signify a farmer holding lands from, and bound by loyalty to, a lord; from this developed the sense of a free landholder as opposed to a serf. In England after the Norman Conquest the word sank in status and became associated with the notion of bound servitude. The name can also be a variant of   Band  .","Swedish: variant of   Bonde  .","In some cases also an American shortened form of Ukrainian   Bondarenko   and possibly also of some other surname beginning with <i>Bond-</i>."]}]},{"name":"Beatrice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["and French form of   Beatrix  , which was quite popular in England during the Middle Ages, and strongly revived in the 19th century. It is most famous as the name of Dante's beloved, and is borne by the elder (  b. 1988 ) of the Duke of York's daughters."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Beatrice de Gand was born in 1040, in Nettlecombe, Somerset, England, United Kingdom, her father, Henry De Bourbourg, was 39 and her mother, Sibilla Rose Guines, was 36. She had at least 1 son with Walter de Raleigh II. She died in 1100, in her hometown, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1040–1100":"1040–1100","1040–1066":"1040–1066","1065–1101":"1065–1101","1001–1052":"1001–1052","1005–1059":"1005–1059","1005":"1005","1059":"1059","1101":"1101","1100":"1100","1001":"1001","1066":"1066","1065":"1065","14 October 1066, killed in the Battle of Hastings":"14. oktoober 1066","1052":"1052","1040":"1040","Hastings, Sussex, England":"Hastings, Sussex, England","Pilton, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Pilton, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Nettlecombe, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Nettlecombe, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bourbouncy, Loe-Et-Garonne, Aquitaine, France":"Aquitaine, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1040–1100":"1040–1100","1040–1066":"1040–1066","1065–1101":"1065–1101","1001–1052":"1001–1052","1005–1059":"1005–1059","1005":"1005","1059":"1059","1101":"1101","1100":"1100","1001":"1001","1066":"1066","1065":"1065","14 October 1066, killed in the Battle of Hastings":"14. lokakuuta 1066","1052":"1052","1040":"1040","Hastings, Sussex, England":"Hastings, Sussex, England","Pilton, Dev